## Bluesky Soft Launch Strategy (March 2026)

### Principles

- Hook with a stark fact, develop with context, land with a link
- Prohibition framing: "No person should..." (project convention)
- Every post earns the click — do not summarize the whole page
- 300-char limit per post forces clarity; use threads for complex arguments
- Reply to every substantive response — Bluesky rewards conversation
- Never delete — fair witness principle; correct publicly if needed
- Alt text on any images — accessibility commitment carries to social
- Hashtags: sparingly, 1-2 per post max (`#HumanRights` `#ICESCR` `#AIEconomics` `#TreatyRatification`)

### Cadence

- Launch weeks (1-2): post every 1-2 days
- Sustained: 2-3x/week
- Timing: weekday mornings (9-11am ET) for professional audience; evenings for general

### Post 1 — The Anchor (Day 1) — Pin to profile

**Format: 4-post thread**

> **1/4** 173 nations ratified a treaty protecting economic rights — work, healthcare, education, an adequate standard of living.
>
> The United States signed it in 1977. The Senate has never voted on it.
>
> Now AI reshapes the economy faster than any technology since electrification.

> **2/4** No person should lose access to healthcare because automation eliminated their job.
>
> No worker should face poverty wages while AI generates record corporate profits.
>
> The treaty that addresses this already exists. It just needs ratification.

> **3/4** We built a full analysis — differential diagnosis of AI's economic impact, four orders of knock-on effects, and what the ICESCR would actually change.
>
> Fair witness methodology. Every claim sourced. Open data.
>
> unratified.org

> **4/4** The blog covers what changes next — legislative developments, methodology, advocacy strategy.
>
> Built by a Claude Code agent. CC BY-SA 4.0. Revision history on GitHub.
>
> blog.unratified.org

### Post 2 — The Stat (Day 2)

> The U.S. has signed but never ratified the ICESCR.
>
> So has Palau. And Comoros.
>
> Every NATO ally ratified it. Every G7 nation except the U.S. ratified it. 173 nations total.
>
> The treaty protects the right to work, health, education, and an adequate standard of living.
>
> unratified.org/gap/

### Post 3 — The AI Hook (Day 3)

> AI functions as narrow superintelligence for software labor. It removes constraints that previously blocked economic activity.
>
> That triggers a Jevons-style demand explosion — bounded by new bottlenecks: regulation, energy, trust, human judgment.
>
> Who benefits depends entirely on whether legal frameworks exist to distribute the gains.
>
> unratified.org/connection/differential-diagnosis/

### Post 4 — The Question (Day 4)

> Genuine question: do you know what economic rights your country's constitution protects?
>
> The U.S. Constitution protects civil and political rights (speech, assembly, due process). It says nothing about the right to work, healthcare, education, or housing.
>
> 173 nations chose to fill that gap. The U.S. did not.

*(No link — engagement post. Invite replies. Link in follow-up reply if thread develops.)*

### Post 5 — The Education Angle (Day 6)

> The most pivotal finding in the AI-economics analysis: as AI handles more cognitive tasks, the bottleneck migrates to human judgment.
>
> Judgment develops through practice and experience. AI cannot substitute for that process.
>
> Article 13 of the ICESCR — the right to education — becomes the linchpin.
>
> unratified.org/covenant/articles/article-13/

